Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.08,0:00:06.66,English,,0,0,0,,Today I'd like to talk about... Zool 2
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.68,0:00:13.32,English,,0,0,0,,for the PC, this is the CD-ROM version and there's a very good reason for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.72,0:00:24.84,English,,0,0,0,,You see, this video isn't really about the game itself, even though it's a pretty decent
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.84,0:00:29.98,English,,0,0,0,,little platformer developed by Gemlin Graphics from 1994.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.98,0:00:37.16,English,,0,0,0,,It's not even about the box contents, including a Zooz postcard, sheet of stickers, depictive
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.16,0:00:41.82,English,,0,0,0,,manual or even this splendidly coloured poster.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.82,0:00:48.35,English,,0,0,0,,It's about that CD, which incidentally, isn't really necessary for this game.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.35,0:00:55.20,English,,0,0,0,,You see, during the mid '90s, CD-ROM was an important, emerging technology, and so even
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.20,0:01:02.74,English,,0,0,0,,games which could fit on a single High Density disk, were baked into CD format, perhaps with
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.74,0:01:06.72,English,,0,0,0,,a new 3D rendered intro, or a selection of music.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.84,0:01:11.22,English,,0,0,0,,but nothing really that warranted the expense of a CD-ROM drive.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.54,0:01:18.10,English,,0,0,0,,But it also meant that the odd warning would appear on disks from certain publishers, warning
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.11,0:01:25.08,English,,0,0,0,,us to "Not play track 1 of this game CD on ANY audio CD Player".
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.42,0:01:28.64,English,,0,0,0,,So, it would seem rude not to really.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.28,0:01:34.20,English,,0,0,0,,For this task, I'll be using a Sanyo MCD-Z10 Boombox.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.70,0:01:41.46,English,,0,0,0,,A fine looking machine which oozes that mid 90s sound appeal, an era when we were moving
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.46,0:01:47.25,English,,0,0,0,,rapidly away from cassette tape and onto that new circular digital medium.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.25,0:01:51.24,English,,0,0,0,,To demonstrate its versatility, first I'll pop in a tape.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.24,0:01:56.74,English,,0,0,0,,Here I have The Crystal Mountain, by Nightlights (otherwise known as Snowkitten)
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.58,0:02:07.78,English,,0,0,0,,I've been listening to their stuff for years, and I love albums on tape, so this is no exception.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.78,0:02:13.48,English,,0,0,0,,There's a bit of wow and flutter from this system, but I imagine a few new bands and
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.48,0:02:17.31,English,,0,0,0,,a bit of grease would clean that right up.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.31,0:02:19.56,English,,0,0,0,,Anyway onto the CD.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.70,0:02:30.34,English,,0,0,0,,Right, track 1, let's see what all the fuss is really about.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.38,0:02:42.38,English,,0,0,0,,Homer: Oh, this was a popular song in the 90s, and\N I really don't understand why you young people like it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.92,0:02:44.92,English,,0,0,0,,Peter Leigh: Welcome to Rick Roll country
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.90,0:02:49.12,English,,0,0,0,,Are they being serious?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.34,0:02:55.98,English,,0,0,0,,Wait, Ahhh, man, I must have picked up the wrong CD.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.12,0:02:59.78,English,,0,0,0,,Yep, there you go I left Rick Astley right next to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:59.78,0:03:03.30,English,,0,0,0,,Ho ho, easy mistake to make!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.30,0:03:05.50,English,,0,0,0,,Let's try that again.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.20,0:03:28.86,English,,0,0,0,,and there we have it, absolutely nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.87,0:03:31.16,English,,0,0,0,,No sound what-so-ever.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.16,0:03:36.62,English,,0,0,0,,It's also the only track on the disc, so it seems a strange disc to place that warning
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.62,0:03:38.09,English,,0,0,0,,on in the first place.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.09,0:03:43.00,English,,0,0,0,,If there were some audio tracks on here as well - as was common on a lot of CD games
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.00,0:03:48.50,English,,0,0,0,,of the time - then it would have made more sense to play this disc on an audio player.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.00,0:03:54.98,English,,0,0,0,,Also, I find it a little amusing that the track length is 4:04.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.98,0:04:00.76,English,,0,0,0,,So just like a 404 wepage error, the contents of this track are apparently absent.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.22,0:04:07.68,English,,0,0,0,,But, it might be that we just need to try a different CD player to get a true idea of
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.68,0:04:09.66,English,,0,0,0,,what's going on here.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.66,0:04:14.26,English,,0,0,0,,ok, so now I'm at my parent's house and they have a Grundig stereo from
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.26,0:04:17.36,English,,0,0,0,,about... what is it? 1995?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.36,0:04:18.14,English,,0,0,0,,Mother: ummm, yes?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.14,0:04:21.54,English,,0,0,0,,About '95, '94. So, let's see if it works with this one...
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.80,0:04:27.40,English,,0,0,0,,Now, I have a sneaky suspicion that we might get a different output from this system.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.40,0:04:31.18,English,,0,0,0,,which I'll explain more about, in a second. Let's try
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.86,0:04:54.94,English,,0,0,0,,Ahhhh, yes, there we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.94,0:05:01.94,English,,0,0,0,,Now THIS is what the warning is for. It's nothing outrageous or shocking really is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.08,0:05:05.70,English,,0,0,0,,This time, we're just hearing this Grundig unit play the raw binary patterns from the
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.71,0:05:09.30,English,,0,0,0,,data track as audio.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.30,0:05:14.18,English,,0,0,0,,It's not going to destroy your system, or send you foaming at the mouth, but I guess
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.18,0:05:22.04,English,,0,0,0,,if you had the volume turned up high, it might cause auditory pain, or at worst, blow your speakers.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.30,0:05:28.24,English,,0,0,0,,So, how come the Sanyo played nothing, yet this Grundig system emited what can only be
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.24,0:05:32.06,English,,0,0,0,,described as a ZX Spectrum tape on steroids?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.94,0:05:39.58,English,,0,0,0,,Oh also, thank you to my parents for letting me borrow this stereo we bought in the mid '90s
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.20,0:05:45.24,English,,0,0,0,,The reason for this is due to how these sound systems are designed.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.10,0:05:54.38,English,,0,0,0,,But to explain the design, we first must look at the structure of the data on a CD.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.66,0:06:02.96,English,,0,0,0,,The Compact Disc Digital Audio standard was established in the joint Philips and Sony
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.96,0:06:10.29,English,,0,0,0,,Red Book release way back in 1981 - the red book being essentially just a rule book named
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.29,0:06:17.00,English,,0,0,0,,so, after it's binding colour, but it's also the start of a rainbow of these books, defining
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.00,0:06:18.85,English,,0,0,0,,further standards.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.85,0:06:24.97,English,,0,0,0,,The yellow book would follow in 1984, and its purpose was to define the Compact Disc
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.97,0:06:27.19,English,,0,0,0,,Read Only Memory format.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.19,0:06:32.94,English,,0,0,0,,The same format - of course - used to store data on this Zool 2 CD.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.94,0:06:39.49,English,,0,0,0,,The significant difference between the two is that the audio CD allows for 2,352 bytes
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.49,0:06:46.42,English,,0,0,0,,per sector (or timecode frames, if you prefer), plus 98 control bytes which hold the timing
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.42,0:06:50.47,English,,0,0,0,,information which you see on your Stereo LCD display.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.00,0:06:56.28,English,,0,0,0,,The CD-ROM structure however, splits that sector up into 12 bytes for synchronisation,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.28,0:07:03.75,English,,0,0,0,,4 bytes for header information, 288 bytes for error correction and 2,048 bytes for the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.75,0:07:05.62,English,,0,0,0,,actual data itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.62,0:07:11.31,English,,0,0,0,,So, if you put a CD with a data track into a fairly recent CD player, it will be able
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.31,0:07:15.91,English,,0,0,0,,to recognise the data track structure and either throw you an error when you try and
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.91,0:07:21.83,English,,0,0,0,,play it, or in the case of my Sanyo, simply silence out the noise of what it perceives
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.83,0:07:24.34,English,,0,0,0,,as incorrectly structured data.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.34,0:07:28.80,English,,0,0,0,,If you have an older stereo, which hasn't been programmed to ascertain whether data
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.80,0:07:34.66,English,,0,0,0,,is actually formatted as Compact Disc Digital Audio before belting it out, then it will
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.66,0:07:37.20,English,,0,0,0,,simply attempt to play it as it comes.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.20,0:07:42.13,English,,0,0,0,,Despite the differences in the format, the stereo will just start reading a large, single
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.14,0:07:46.82,English,,0,0,0,,track of - what it presumes to be sweet, sweet melody - which it will stream directly out
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.52,0:07:57.70,English,,0,0,0,,I mean, the chances of someone even having a CD-ROM to put in their spanking new CD player
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.71,0:08:03.36,English,,0,0,0,,were incredibly low until the mid 90s, so building in these checks just wasn't deemed
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.36,0:08:04.26,English,,0,0,0,,that necessary.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.50,0:08:13.84,English,,0,0,0,,But you may point out that the Grundig stereo is actually from the mid 90s, and about the
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.84,0:08:18.10,English,,0,0,0,,same age as the Sanyo, so how come the difference in playback?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.02,0:08:23.28,English,,0,0,0,,Well, this, as I suspected is down to the quality of the goods.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.29,0:08:28.12,English,,0,0,0,,Both systems are modern enough to weed out data tracks, however, because the Grundig
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.12,0:08:33.96,English,,0,0,0,,is a cheaper system, it likely utilises components which just don't care.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.96,0:08:41.39,English,,0,0,0,,Perhaps older components, or just cheaper components, but regardless, the Grundig has
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.39,0:08:48.19,English,,0,0,0,,no idea as to what a data track is, so it does it's best to play it as CD audio, and
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.19,0:08:54.58,English,,0,0,0,,it really is the CD player attempting to process the binary pits and lands of the CD surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.58,0:08:56.92,English,,0,0,0,,as an uncompressed wave format.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.99,0:09:05.22,English,,0,0,0,,The result of this, is noise streaming in at a relatively high baud rate, and if we
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.23,0:09:10.67,English,,0,0,0,,slow down the audio, perhaps to a more familiar speed, then it starts to sound just a little
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.67,0:09:14.16,English,,0,0,0,,bit more like an 80s home computer
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.26,0:09:20.66,English,,0,0,0,,ahhhhh, yes
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.92,0:09:24.06,English,,0,0,0,,or even a dial up modem from the 90s.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.06,0:09:26.28,English,,0,0,0,,it's blissful
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.42,0:09:28.57,English,,0,0,0,,I could just drift off to this.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.58,0:09:31.32,English,,0,0,0,,Maybe we'll play Zool 2 another day.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.58,0:09:36.14,English,,0,0,0,,Now this might have been a bit of a silly video
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.34,0:09:40.24,English,,0,0,0,,but hopefully I've explained a few noggins of interest.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.24,0:09:42.84,English,,0,0,0,,That's all I can hope for really.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.84,0:09:47.14,English,,0,0,0,,Anyway, thanks for watching, and hopefully, I'll see you next time!
